tomia is dry mouth from decreased saliva production; sialolithiasis may lead to bacterial infection due to the formation of stones; mucocele occurs from gland rupture with saliva leakage","Xerostomia occurs from gland rupture with saliva leakage; sialolithiasis causes dry mouth; mucocele leads to bacterial infection due to the formation of stones","Xerostomia leads to bacterial infection due to the formation of stones; sialolithiasis occurs from gland rupture with saliva leakage; mucocele causes dry mouth","Xerostomia occurs from gland rupture with saliva leakage; sialolithiasis leads to bacterial infection due to the formation of stones; mucocele causes dry mouth","Xerostomia leads to bacterial infection due to the formation of stones; sialolithiasis causes dry mouth; mucocele occurs from gland rupture with saliva leakage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EXerostomia\u003C/strong\u003E is the subjective sensation of dry mouth that results from decreased saliva production. This can occur due to medications, radiation therapy, or autoimmune conditions like Sj\u00f6gren syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESialolithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to stone formation within salivary ducts. These stones can obstruct normal saliva flow and lead to bacterial infection, commonly involving \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus viridans\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emucocele\u003C/strong\u003E develops when salivary glands or their ducts are damaged or blocked, causing saliva to leak into the surrounding soft tissues. This creates a painless, fluid-filled swelling typically on the lower lip.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Xerostomia is the subjective sensation of dry mouth due to decreased saliva production","Sialolithiasis refers to stone formation in salivary ducts and can lead to bacterial infection","Mucocele occurs when salivary glands or ducts are damaged, leading to saliva leakage into surrounding tissues"],"references":["Sarbia M, Becker KF, H\u00f6fler H. Pathology of upper gastrointestinal malignancies. Semin Oncol. 2004 Aug;31(4):465-75. doi: 10.1053/j.seminoncol.2004.04.020. PMID: 15297939.","Nallasivam KU, Sudha BR. Oral mucocele: Review of literature and a case report. J Pharm Bioallied Sci. 2015 Aug;7(Suppl 2):S731-3. doi: 10.4103/0975-7406.163516. PMID: 26538955; PMCID: PMC4606697.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54760"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15171"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54760"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:07:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:10:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7862"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69307"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{